output 2.dc_description_s: Woolpert completed a semi-automated method for building generation utilizing new countywide 2009 LiDAR data and existing 2005-2008 orthoimagery. Buildings over 100 square feet were generated and run through a QC process. The final building polygons were developed for the entire 709 square mile county area. The dataset has had all but those footprints near or within the City of Ann Arbor and contains an average building height.
dc_creator_sm: City of Ann Arbor - Community Services

output 3.dc_description_s: This feature class displays all of the largest drainage areas in Washtenaw County. It has been developed to meet the needs of upstream and downstream network tracing by Washtenaw County employees and citizens. This data was created from delenations of a mosaiced grid comprised of USGS Quadrangle DEMs. The data was then conflated with perspective stream reach information.

output 5.dc_title_s: Downtown Development Authority Boundary: Ann Arbor, Michigan, 2010
output 5.dc_description_s: The City of Ann Arbor created the Ann Arbor DDA (Ordinance No. 14-82) in 1982 and renewed it in 2003 with a substantial amendment to its original Development Plan. Over its history, the DDA has been a significant and influential catalyst for the revitalization and renewal of downtown Ann Arbor. The Ann Arbor Downtown Development District encompasses all or part of 66 city blocks, or approximately 271 acres, of which 80 acres are public rights-of-way.
dc_creator_sm: City of Ann Arbor - Community Services

output 7.dc_description_s: That portion of the river valley, adjacent to the channel, which is built of sediments deposited during the present geological / climatic regime. Created by the City of Ann Arbor Systems Planning using FEMA data. This resource is now being updated by Systems Planning using newest FEMA data.

output 21.dc_description_s: This feature dataclass was created with the intentions of displaying all of the school districts whose boundaries are located within Washtenaw County.  The boundaries were created by dissolving the current Washtenaw County parcels layer by the school district field.  In order to maintain the attributes of the old school districts file, we then lined up the boundaries from the old school districts map with the dissolved layer.  After the boundaries were lined up, topology was created in order to verify that there were no topological errors within the feature dataclass.

output 34.dc_description_s: A 'Regulatory Floodway' means the channel of a river or other watercourse and the adjacent land areas that must be reserved in order to discharge the base flood without cumulatively increasing the water surface elevation more than a designated height. Communities must regulate development in these floodways to ensure that there are no increases in upstream flood elevations. For streams and other watercourses where FEMA has provided Base Flood Elevations (BFEs) but no floodway has been designated, the community must review floodplain development on a case-by-case basis to ensure that increases in water surface elevations do not occur, or identify the need to adopt a floodway if adequate information is available. Created by Systems Planning based using FEMA floodplain info. In the process of being updated based on newest FEMA data.
